{{Infobox person | name = Namrata Singh Gujral | image = Namrata Singh Gujral on the set of Americanizing Shelley.JPG | caption = Namrata Singh Gujral on the set of ''Americanizing Shelley'' | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1976|2|26|mf=y}} | birth_place = [[Dharamshala, Himachal Pradesh]], India | death_date = | death_place = | occupation = Film, television actress | nationality = American }}
'''Namrata Singh Gujral''' (born February 26, 1976) is an American director, producer and actor.
==Life and career== Gujral was born in [[Dharamshala, Himachal Pradesh|Dharamshala]], [[Himachal Pradesh]], but left India at a young age.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.openchest.com/oc-in-print/actress-namrata-singh-gujral|author=Raj Girn|title=Namrata Singh Gujral Carves Her Own Niche In Hollywood|publisher=ANOKHI|date=2007-04-01|accessdate=2015-07-16}}</ref> A devout [[Sikh]] by faith, she graduated in 1998 from the [[University of West Florida]].
In 2013, she was treated for [[Burkitt's lymphoma]]. She was treated with aggressive chemotherapy including [[intrathecal]] [[chemotherapy]] at [[City of Hope National Medical Center|City of Hope]] for six months. The cause of [[lymphoma]] was prior chemotherapy from 2008 for [[breast cancer]]. In 2013, Gujral was in remission from both cancers.<ref name="Lisa Tsering">{{cite web|url=http://www.indiawest.com/news/12691-Actress-Fights-Lymphoma--Urges-Community-Awareness.html|author=Lisa Tsering|title=Actress fights lymphoma Urges Community Awareness|publisher=India West|date=2013-08-06|accessdate=2015-06-28|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131211103350/http://www.indiawest.com/news/12691-Actress-Fights-Lymphoma--Urges-Community-Awareness.html|archivedate=2013-12-11|df=}}</ref>
In 2008, Gujral was treated for early stage, invasive [[breast cancer]]. She underwent surgery and chemotherapy. She hosts ''Thrive! With Namrata'', a panel based show with cancer survivors on the ''Thrive Channel''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thrivechannel.com/campaigns |title=Thrive with Namrata |publisher=Thrive Channel |accessdate=2015-06-28}}</ref> She is featured in [[Uniglobe Entertainment]]'s cancer docu-drama titled ''[[1 a Minute]]'' released in 600 theaters. This is the largest release to date for a cancer-related film in cinema history. The docudrama is directed and produced by Gujral and also stars breast cancer survivors [[Olivia Newton-John]], [[Diahann Carroll]], [[Melissa Etheridge]], [[Mumtaz (actress)|Mumtaz]], [[Jaclyn Smith]] and cancer survivors [[Lisa Ray]], [[Barbara Mori]] and cancer treatment advocates [[Deepak Chopra]], [[William Baldwin]], [[Daniel Baldwin]], [[Priya Dutt]] and [[Nancy Brinker]]. This marked Gujral's directorial debut.<ref name="Lisa Tsering"/>
==Music== Gujral made her singing debut with the single "Dancin' In The Clouds", an American [[country rock]] meets [[Bollywood]] style duet, with country star [[Steve Azar]], currently playing on [[Country Music Television]]. The single also features on MTV and VH1. Hollywood composer [[Jay Ferguson (American musician)|Jay Ferguson]] of [[Spirit]] and [[Jo Jo Gunne]] fame produced the single, reportedly making her the first American artist with Eastern roots to be featured on [[Country Music Television|CMT]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cmt.com/loaded/player.jhtml?vid=138707|title=Steve Azar & Namrata Singh Gujral "Dancin' in the Clouds"|publisher=CMT|accessdate=2015-06-28}}</ref>
==Awards== * AskMen.Com's "Actress-Of-The-Week" in November 2007.<ref>[http://www.askmen.com/women/celeb_profiles_actress_100/107_namrata_singh_gujral.html Namrata Singh Gujral], AskMen.com; retrieved January 1, 2012.</ref> * For her role as Saira Ahmed on the CBS series ''[[Family Law (TV series)|Family Law]]'', Gujral, along with co-stars [[Tony Danza]] and [[Kathleen Quinlan]], were [[Columbia TriStar Television|Columbia TriStar]]'s official nomination for the 2002 [[Emmy Award]]s.
